{"id": 59751, "date": "2025-10-02T04:00:53", "date_gmt": "2025-10-02T11:00:53", "guid": {"rendered": "https://estreetshuffle.com/?p=59751"}, "modified": "2026-06-11T08:30:07", "modified_gmt": "2026-06-11T15:30:07", "slug": "kingdom-of-days-october-2-2", "status": "publish", "type": "post", "link": "https://estreetshuffle.com/index.php/2025/10/02/kingdom-of-days-october-2-2/", "title": {"rendered": "October 2"}, "content": {"rendered": "<p><em><strong>New for 2025:\u00a0</strong>Review for 2004</em></p>\n<p><strong>1971:\u00a0</strong>The Bruce Springsteen Band is in residence at the Student Prince in Asbury Park.</p>\n<p><strong>1975:\u00a0</strong>Bruce plays his first-ever show in the state of Wisconsin, at the Uptown Theater in Milwaukee. Partway through the first set, the show is halted due to a bomb threat, and the band and audience adjourn for three hours while security sweeps the place. The band takes up temporary residence at the Hotel Pfister bar, and by the time the show resumes at midnight (with the live debut of &#8220;<a href=\"http://estreetshuffle.com/index.php/2018/12/11/cover-me-little-queenie/\">Little Queenie</a>,&#8221; the band is, um, loose. The ensuing second set will become legend, known forever after as &#8220;The Bomb Scare Show,&#8221; with a <em>very</em> buzzed Springsteen enjoying himself immensely and continually asking the audience, &#8220;Are you loose?&#8221;</p>\n<div class=\"jetpack-video-wrapper\"><span class=\"embed-youtube\" style=\"text-align:center; display: block;\"><iframe loading=\"lazy\" class=\"youtube-player\" width=\"758\" height=\"427\" src=\"https://www.youtube.com/embed/NvVtJcsz7hc?version=3&#038;rel=1&#038;showsearch=0&#038;showinfo=1&#038;iv_load_policy=1&#038;fs=1&#038;hl=en-US&#038;autohide=2&#038;wmode=transparent\" allowfullscreen=\"true\" style=\"border:0;\" sandbox=\"allow-scripts allow-same-origin allow-popups allow-presentation allow-popups-to-escape-sandbox\"></iframe></span></div>\n<div class=\"jetpack-v